WEBVTT

00:00:10.980 --> 00:00:15.130
>> We really appreciate the travel
time you took to come here.

00:00:15.130 --> 00:00:21.550
The energy the student community brings to the
Developer's Conference is always reflected back

00:00:21.550 --> 00:00:26.530
to the engineering community and the other
attendees as a really positive experience.

00:00:26.530 --> 00:00:34.240
And we want to give you some sign posts and
guidance today to help you maximize that energy

00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:39.450
and to help you take the best advantage of
the Developer's Conference for this year.

00:00:39.450 --> 00:00:45.750
The first thing I'm going to start off with is just
talking about what the point of your being here is.

00:00:45.750 --> 00:00:47.869
It's not just a week of fun.

00:00:47.869 --> 00:00:52.049
It's a week of your future for most of you in the room.

00:00:52.049 --> 00:00:59.099
It's an opportunity for you to interact with
professional software developers both from Apple

00:00:59.100 --> 00:01:08.090
and from a great many third parties from information
technology organizations and from large universities.

00:01:08.090 --> 00:01:09.799
Take advantage of that time.

00:01:09.799 --> 00:01:15.640
This is probably one of the few times in your career where
you'll have the opportunity to interact with people

00:01:15.640 --> 00:01:19.650
from skill levels from super guru to beginner.

00:01:19.650 --> 00:01:25.969
And get in their heads, but don't get in their way.

00:01:25.969 --> 00:01:29.409
There's a lot of conversation going on in the hallways.

00:01:29.409 --> 00:01:31.799
Participate by standing around and listening.

00:01:31.799 --> 00:01:34.090
If you're invited in, join in.

00:01:34.090 --> 00:01:36.210
But do a lot of listening.

00:01:36.209 --> 00:01:42.829
Pay attention to what your fellow programmers, who may have
a lot more years under their belts, are paying attention to

00:01:42.829 --> 00:01:47.659
and are talking about, because that's going to
guide you on what's important for your career.

00:01:47.659 --> 00:01:52.969
And a lot of what this is is basic hallway hygiene.

00:01:52.969 --> 00:01:56.730
The other thing to think about is what you want to do.

00:01:56.730 --> 00:02:04.130
We have three real important clientele
in this building this year.

00:02:04.129 --> 00:02:11.769
We have the information technology folks, two tracks, two
rooms full of information technology subjects all week long.

00:02:11.770 --> 00:02:18.420
We have the traditional API developers doing
Cocoa, doing Carbon, doing UNIX programming.

00:02:18.419 --> 00:02:21.009
Do you fit into that community?

00:02:21.009 --> 00:02:23.780
And then third is content and media.

00:02:23.780 --> 00:02:30.300
This morning one of the things that I hope that you take
away from the keynote and what you have an advantage

00:02:30.300 --> 00:02:34.330
over someone, like me quite frankly, is Web 2.0 and Ajax.

00:02:34.330 --> 00:02:38.550
That's the way to develop an application for the iPhone.

00:02:38.550 --> 00:02:43.660
It's a way to develop an application
for Safari on Mac and on Windows.

00:02:43.659 --> 00:02:49.189
Go to those sessions, dive into that and
show us the way to be creative with that.

00:02:49.189 --> 00:02:52.840
Some of us have been around too long
to have new ideas in those spaces.

00:02:52.840 --> 00:02:59.770
So take advantage of your fresh viewpoint in there
and get some ideas that are going to surprise all of us.

00:02:59.770 --> 00:03:11.540
And finally, this is your chance to look eye to eye with a
software developer at our developer bash on Thursday night,

00:03:11.539 --> 00:03:16.629
or at lunch, or in the evenings and
say, tell me what it's really like.

00:03:16.629 --> 00:03:25.419
I may have spent all this time in high school,
in college, in post doc or post graduate studies,

00:03:25.419 --> 00:03:28.509
learning how to do something called software.

00:03:28.509 --> 00:03:37.699
But what is it really like when eight to 16 hours
a day, five to seven days a week, you're writing

00:03:37.699 --> 00:03:42.149
and debugging code, code that's not yours?

00:03:42.150 --> 00:03:50.270
Code that may be going into a database application
that powers American Airlines' reservation system?

00:03:50.270 --> 00:03:58.219
Or it may be something as compelling as a game, but
you're only doing the file system portion of it.

00:03:58.219 --> 00:04:04.569
Learn from people here how they survive those times
of it's not really creative, it's not really fun,

00:04:04.569 --> 00:04:09.120
it's a grind of being a programmer day to day.

00:04:09.120 --> 00:04:11.310
You'll find from a lot of them that it's not a grind.

00:04:11.310 --> 00:04:12.830
It's still a lot of fun.

00:04:12.830 --> 00:04:17.750
But the transition from being in the academic
side of learning how to become a programmer,

00:04:17.750 --> 00:04:24.670
to actually being a coder, watch the labs, watch people
in the hallways, and if you have the opportunity,

00:04:24.670 --> 00:04:32.390
talk to people about their experiences and what saved
their sanity in their progress to being master programmers.

00:04:32.389 --> 00:04:34.669
That's your opportunity this week.

00:04:34.670 --> 00:04:40.629
Many people don't get that opportunity as they
transition from school to the professional community.

00:04:40.629 --> 00:04:42.490
Take advantage of it.

00:04:42.490 --> 00:04:47.509
Now I'd like to bring up Michael to give
you some more perspectives on the week.

00:04:47.509 --> 00:04:52.079
( Applause )

00:04:52.079 --> 00:04:53.399
>> Michael: Thanks, CK.

00:04:53.399 --> 00:04:58.339
So CK is actually my boss's boss, so I
have to watch what I say when I'm up here.

00:04:58.339 --> 00:05:00.829
Excellent that'll make it a lot easier.

00:05:00.829 --> 00:05:01.620
All right.

00:05:01.620 --> 00:05:03.490
So my name's Michael Jurewitz.

00:05:03.490 --> 00:05:08.329
I work as a developer technical support
engineer, so I work in CK's organization.

00:05:08.329 --> 00:05:13.979
My job is to work with 3rd party developers like
yourselves, like those who are premiere and select members,

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:17.230
and I answer code level questions
that come into our frameworks.

00:05:17.230 --> 00:05:20.800
I focus primarily on Core Data, Cocoa, and bindings.

00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:23.329
So if you see me throughout the
week, feel free to ask me a question.

00:05:23.329 --> 00:05:28.029
So first and foremost, welcome
to everyone of you who are here.

00:05:28.029 --> 00:05:32.969
This is a really exciting WWDC for all
of us, especially for the students.

00:05:32.970 --> 00:05:37.590
We have over 450 of you from oPver 30 countries.

00:05:37.589 --> 00:05:42.500
